definition: ENA|AEV14992|AEV14992.1 Xenopipo atronitens (black manakin) partial cytochrome oxidase subunit 1

LengthCluster.description: Check whether the prediction length fits most of the BLAST hit lengths, by 1D hierarchical clusterization. Meaning of the output displayed: Query_length [Main Cluster Length Interval]
LengthCluster.approach: If the query sequence is well conserved and similar sequences (BLAST hits) are correct, we can expect query and hit sequences to have similar lengths. Here, we cluster the lengths of hit sequences and compare the length of our query sequence to the most dense cluster of hit lengths.
LengthCluster.explanation: The most dense length-cluster of BLAST hits includes sequences that are from 505 to 541 amino-acids long. The query sequence is 217 amino-acids long and is thus outside the most dense length-cluster of BLAST hits.
LengthCluster.conclusion: This suggests that the query sequence may be too short.

LengthRank.description: Check whether the rank of the prediction length lies among 80% of all the BLAST hit lengths.
LengthRank.approach: If the query sequence is well conserved and similar sequences (BLAST hits) are correct, we can expect query and hit sequences to have similar lengths.
LengthRank.explanation: The query sequence is  217 amino-acids long. BLAST identified 229 hit sequences with lengths from 58 to 873 amino-acids (median: 517; mean: 531). 6 of these hit sequences (i.e. 3%) are shorter than the query sequence.
LengthRank.conclusion: The sequence may be too short.

GeneMerge.description: Check whether BLAST hits make evidence about a merge of two genes that match the predicted gene.
GeneMerge.approach: We expect the query sequence to encode a single protein-coding gene. Here, we analyse the High-scoring Segment Pairs (HSPs) identified by BLAST to determine whether the query includes sequence from two or more genes.
GeneMerge.explanation: The start coordinates and the end coordinates of HSPs are unimodally distributed.
GeneMerge.conclusion: This suggest that the query sequence represents a single gene.

Gene Merge Validation: Query coord covered by blast hit (1 line/hit)

Duplication.description: Check whether there is a duplicated subsequence in the predicted gene by counting the hsp residue coverage of the prediction, for each hit.
Duplication.approach: We expect each BLAST hit to match each region of the query at most once. Here, we calculate the distribution of hit coverage against the query sequence and use the Wilcoxon test to determine if it is higher than 1.
Duplication.explanation: The Wilcoxon test produced a p-value of 1.
Duplication.conclusion: This suggests that the query sequence contains no erroneous duplications.

ReadingFrame.description: Check whether there is a single reading frame among BLAST hits. Otherwise there might be a reading frame shift in the query sequence.
ReadingFrame.approach: We expect the query sequence to encode a single gene, thus it should contain one main Open Reading Frame (ORF). All BLAST hits are thus expected to align within this ORF.
ReadingFrame.explanation: BLAST identified 229 High-scoring Segment Pairs (HSPs); all of these align in frame 2.

MainORF.description: Check whether there is a single main Open Reading Frame in the predicted gene. Applicable only for nucleotide queries.
MainORF.approach: We expect the query sequence to encode a single gene, thus it should contain one main Open Reading Frame (ORF) that occupies most of the query sequence.
MainORF.explanation: The longest ORF is in frame -2, where it occupies 45% of the query sequence.
MainORF.conclusion: This only represents a portion of the query sequence. In some cases this indicates that a frame shift exists in the query sequence.

MissingExtraSequences.description: Finds missing and extra sequences in the prediction, based on the multiple alignment of the best hits. Also counts the percentage of the conserved regions that appear in the prediction.
MissingExtraSequences.approach: We expect the query sequence to be similar to the top ten BLAST hits. Here, we create a statistical consensus model of those top hits and compare the query to this model.
MissingExtraSequences.explanation: The query sequence includes 14% amino-acid residues present in the consensus model. 6% of residues in the query sequence are absent from the consensus profile.  60% of residues in the consensus profile are absent from the query sequence.
MissingExtraSequences.conclusion: These results suggest that there may be some problems with the query sequence. The query sequence has a high percentage (60%) of missing residues when compared to the statistical profile (the cut-off is 20%).
